  <exercises>

    <exercisegroup>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use the point-slope form of the equation of the line to determine the equation of the line that passes through each of the following pairs of points.  In each case state the equation in slope-intercept form.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>            
            <m>(1,-5)</m> and <m>(-2,-32)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We begin by determining the slope of the line.
            <me>(x_1,y_1) \text{ is } (1,-5) \text{ and } (x_2,y_2) \text{ is } (-2,-32)</me>
            <md>
              <mrow>m\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{-32-(-5)}{-2-1}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{-27}{-3}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=9</mrow>
            </md>
            We can use the slope of <m>9</m> along with the ordered pair <m>(1,-5)</m> in the equation <m>y-y_1=m(x-x_1)</m> to determine the equation of the line.
            <md>
              <mrow>y-(-5)\amp=9(x-1)</mrow>
              <mrow>y+5\amp=9x-9</mrow>
              <mrow>y+5\subtractright{5}\amp=9x-9\subtractright{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=9x-14</mrow>
            </md>
            he equation of the line is <m>y=9x-14</m>.  Both points check.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>            
            <m>(36,-1)</m> and <m>(-12,19)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We begin by determining the slope of the line.
            <me>(x_1,y_1) \text{ is } (36,-1) \text{ and } (x_2,y_2) \text{ is } (-12,19)</me>
            <md>
              <mrow>m\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_1-x_1}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{19-(-1)}{-12-36}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{20}{-48}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=-\frac{5}{12}</mrow>
            </md>
            We can use the slope of <m>-\frac{5}{12}</m> along with the ordered pair <m>(36,-1)</m> in the equation <m>y-y_1=m(x-x_1)</m> to determine the equation of the line.
            <md>
              <mrow>y-(-1)\amp=-\frac{5}{12}(x-36)</mrow>
              <mrow>y+1\amp=-\frac{5}{12}x+15</mrow>
              <mrow>y+1\subtractright{1}\amp=-\frac{5}{12}x+15\subtractright{1}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{5}{12}+14</mrow>
            </md>
            So the equation of the line is <m>y=-\frac{5}{12}x+14</m>.  Checks.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>            
            <m>(5,-6)</m> and <m>(-7,-2)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We begin by determining the slope of the line.
            <me>(x_1,y_1) \text{ is } (5,-6) \text{ and } (x_2,y_2) \text{ is } (-7,-2)</me>
            <md>
              <mrow>m\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_1-x_1}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{-2-(-6)}{-7-5}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{4}{-12}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=-\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
            </md>
            We can use the slope of <m>-\frac{1}{3}</m> along with the ordered pair <m>(5,-6)</m> in the equation <m>y-y_1=m(x-x_1)</m> to determine the equation of the line.
            <md>
              <mrow>y-(-6)\amp=-\frac{1}{3}(x-5)</mrow>
              <mrow>y+6\amp=-\frac{1}{3}x+\frac{5}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>y+6\subtractright{6}\amp=-\frac{1}{3}x+\frac{5}{3}\subtractright{\frac{18}{3}}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{1}{3}x-\frac{13}{3}</mrow>
            </md>
            So the equation of the line seems to be <m>y=-\frac{1}{3}x-\frac{13}{3}</m>.  Hmmm ... let's check the point <m>(-7,-2)</m>.
            <md>
              <mrow>-2\amp=-\frac{1}{3} \cdot -7-\frac{13}{3}?</mrow>
              <mrow>-2\amp=\frac{7}{3}-\frac{13}{3}?</mrow>
              <mrow>-2\amp=-\frac{6}{3} \checkmark</mrow>
            </md>
            Well I'll be darned, the equation of the line really is <m>y=-\frac{1}{3}x-\frac{13}{3}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</section>
